SECOND INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON ZIKA VIRUS AND AEDES RELATED INFECTIONS
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 22 Jan 2018
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>


We are pleased to announce the Second International Conference on Zika Virus and Aedes Related Infections to take place in Tallinn, Estonia, 14-17 Jun 2018.

This unique, inter-disciplinary conference will include all _Aedes_ related infections in addition to Zika. _Aedes_ related infections have become a concern and continue to be a global threat with Europe being one of the affected areas. The content of this conference will include: epidemiology and clinical aspects of _Aedes_ related infections, gynecological aspects and follow up with children born to Zika infected mothers. In addition, virology aspects, diagnostic methods, new therapy, and vaccine production, as well as new methods of mosquito control will be discussed in the meeting.

Submit your abstract for Oral and Poster presentation:
https://www.zikaconference2018.com/abstracts

Submission deadline: 28 Feb 2018

Early registration deadline: 3 Apr 2018

Register today:
https://www.zikaconference2018.com/registration

For further details please visit the conference website:
http://www.zikaconference2018.com

Already confirmed as Plenary Speakers are:
- Professor David Baud, University Hospital, Lausanne, Switzerland
Keynote lecture: Congenital Zika Syndrome: Updates and Gaps in Knowledge

- Dr Denis Coulombier, Surveillance and Response Support, European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control, Stockholm, Sweden
Keynote Lecture: _Aedes_ Related Infections: European Point of View

- Professor Duane J Gubler, Duke-NUS Medical School, Singapore
Keynote Lecture: Zika and Other _Aedes_ Transmitted Diseases, Past, Present, and Future

- Professor Paul Reiter, Consultant on mosquitoes and mosquito-borne diseases, France
Keynote Lecture: New Methods for Mosquito Control

- Professor Annelies Wilder-Smith, London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, London, UK & WHO Initiative for Vaccine Research
Keynote Lecture: The Drama of the First Dengue Vaccine

